[1] South Africa (NW Province)
Date: Fri, 2 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: news24.com [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/News/0,,2-7-1442_1507511,00.html>

Cholera: North West baffled
-------------------------
The North West provincial health department was still baffled on Fri, 2 Apr
2004, by the cause of the cholera outbreak in a township in Klerksdorp, a
spokesperson said. Barba Gaoganediwe said tests done on water collected
from the Kanana township were negative for cholera.
"We still don't know where the disease comes from," he said. "But we will
investigate every possible source."
He said underground water sources were also being tested for possible
contamination. Teams from the health department were distributing
educational material to residents of Kanana.
Meanwhile, 20 people were still under observation in hospital. 3 people
were still receiving treatment for cholera after it was confirmed that they
were suffering from the disease. They were in a satisfactory condition,
Gaoganediwe said. 2 other people have already been discharged from hospital.
******
[2] South Africa (NW Province)
Date: Thu, 1 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: SABC News.com [edited]
<http://www.sabcnews.com/south_africa/general/0,2172,77074,00.html>

5 more people admitted for cholera at Klerksdorp
---------------------------------------------------
The number of people admitted to the Klerksdorp hospital in the North West
and confirmed to have contracted cholera, has increased from 4 to 9. 2 are
in serious condition in the Intensive Care Unit. 8 other people suspected
of having contracted the disease are currently undergoing tests.
Kanana township, near Orkney, has a history of rampant outbreaks of
cholera. Past outbreaks of cholera in the area indicate that the victims
may have contracted the disease after using and drinking contaminated
water. The latest outbreak can be attributed to the outdated water supply
system, overcrowding, and the general unhygienic state of the township.
The provincial health department has embarked on immediate steps to correct
the situation. A departmental task team has been appointed to investigate
and identify the source of the outbreak and put measures in place to
contain further spread of the disease.
This is the 2nd outbreak of cholera to be reported in less than 2 years in
the area. In the last incident, 12 cases were reported in Orkney. Most were
caused by a leak from a sewerage pipe at Tau-Lekoa Mine.
[The original post stated that the last outbreak of cholera in this
province was in 2000. As stated in this posting, the outbreak was in 2002.
- Mod.LL]
