[3] South Africa (East Cape)
Date: Thu, 1 Apr 2004 11:19:21 -0400
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Yahoo News, UK [edited]
<http://uk.news.yahoo.com/040401/323/eq2nk.html>

Cholera outbreak in South Africa kills 13
------------------------------------------
13 people have died in a cholera outbreak in rural South Africa in March,
while more than 100 others have been treated for the disease in recent weeks.
Sizwe Kupelo, a spokesman for the Eastern Cape province said Thu, 1 Apr
2004, that 13 people died in 3 villages between the towns of Kokstad and
Umtata in southeastern South Africa in Mar 2004.
Kupelo said the disease was probably spread through dirty water.
"In many of these areas there is no clean water or toilets -- people go to
the toilet in the bush, cholera spreads easily in these circumstances," he
said.
"The municipalities are trying to get permanent clean drinking water and
sanitation facilities into these areas, but they face a huge backlog,"
Kupelo added.
At least 7 million people out of a population of 44.8 million do not have
access to running water in South Africa, making them susceptible to the
water-borne disease.
